<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-207-050  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 207 050.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Mar 1 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Federal judge upholds conviction of Cornell &quot;hacker.&quot; (RobertTappan Morris)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Computer Fraud and Abuse Act of 1986 (interpretation andconstruction).andO;Topic:     Computer hackersLaw Suit.andO;Person:    Morris, Robert T., Jr. (legal status, laws, etc.).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>FEDERAL JUDGE UPHOLDS CONVICTION OF CORNELL &quot;HACKER&quot; ALBANY, NEW YORK,U.S.A,.andP;  1990 FEB 27 (NB) -- U.S.andP;  District Judge Howard Munson has refusedto overturn the conviction of Robert Tappan Morris for planting a computer&quot;worm&quot; that shut down approximately 6,000 computers in November 1988.andM;Morris's attorney, Thomas Guidoboni, had sought to overturn the verdict dueto the use of the word &quot;terrorist&quot; by the prosecutor in describing Morris, aterm the attorney is said to consider highly inflammatory, and on the groundsthat Morris did not, in fact, violate the 1986 Computer Fraud and Abuse Actbut had merely over-stepped the authority given him by Cornell University.andO;The defense had argued that the use of term terrorist was prejudicial whenused to a Syracuse jury 13 months after 35 Syracuse University students werekilled when a terrorist bomb blew up Pan Am flight 103 over Lockerbie,Scotland.andP;  The judge, however, ruled the comment made by prosecutor EllenMeltzer was &quot;an isolated event in a trial free of prejudice,&quot; and said: &quot;Thecourt does not believe the prosecution's statement mandates a new trial.&quot;andM;Morris, indicted in July 1989, was the first person to be prosecuted under aportion of the 1986 Computer Fraud and Abuse Act.andP;  Morris, who is currentlyworking as a programmer at Harvard University, faces up to five years' inprison and a $250,000 fine when sentenced on May 4.andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19900227)</TEXT></DOC>